unemployment (ages 15–34) declined to 44.8% in Q4 2025. Among those aged 15–24, the rate stands at 61.4% — meaning roughly 6 in 10 young South Africans who want work cannot find it. South Africa's youth unemployment is among the highest globally.","source":{"name":"Statistics South Africa","shortName":"Stats SA","url":"https://www.statssa.gov.za/?page_id=1854&PPN=P0211","publicationName":"Quarterly Labour Force Survey Q4 2025","publicationDate":"2026-02-17"},"lastUpdated":"2026-02-17","series":[{"name":"Youth Unemployment Rate (%)","unit":"%","data":[{"label":"Q1 2022","value":47.4},{"label":"Q2 2022","value":47},{"label":"Q3 2022","value":46},{"label":"Q4 2022","value":45.7},{"label":"Q1 2023","value":46.3},{"label":"Q2 2023","value":47.1},{"label":"Q3 2023","value":47.3},{"label":"Q4 2023","value":46.1},{"label":"Q1 2024","value":45.9},{"label":"Q2 2024","value":46.2},{"label":"Q3 2024","value":44.9},{"label":"Q4 2024","value":45.4},{"label":"Q1 2025","value":46.1},{"label":"Q2 2025","value":45.9},{"label":"Q3 2025","value":45.7},{"label":"Q4 2025","value":44.8}]}]},{"id":"labour-force-participation","categoryId":"unemployment","title":"Labour Force Participation Rate","value":"42.7%","rawValue":42.7,"unit":"%","change":-0.1,"changeLabel":"from Q3 2025","trend":"stable","description":"42.7% of working-age South Africans (ages 15–64) were either employed or actively seeking work in Q4 2025. This participation rate remains among the lowest globally, partly reflecting large numbers of discouraged work-seekers who have given up looking for jobs.","source":{"name":"Statistics South Africa","shortName":"Stats SA","url":"https://www.statssa.gov.za/?page_id=1854&PPN=P0211","publicationName":"Quarterly Labour Force Survey Q4 2025","publicationDate":"2026-02-17"},"lastUpdated":"2026-02-17","series":[{"name":"Participation Rate (%)","unit":"%","data":[{"label":"Q1 2023","value":42.8},{"label":"Q2 2023","value":42.5},{"label":"Q3 2023","value":43.1},{"label":"Q4 2023","value":43.2},{"label":"Q1 2024","value":42.9},{"label":"Q2 2024","value":43},{"label":"Q3 2024","value":43.3},{"label":"Q4 2024","value":42.9},{"label":"Q1 2025","value":42.5},{"label":"Q2 2025","value":42.9},{"label":"Q3 2025","value":42.8},{"label":"Q4 2025","value":42.7}]}]},{"id":"youth-unemployment-narrow","categoryId":"unemployment","title":"Youth Unemployment Rate (15–34)","value":"45.5%","rawValue":45.5,"unit":"%","change":-0.8,"changeLabel":"from Q3 2025","trend":"down","description":"Narrow youth unemployment rate for those aged 15–34 who are without work, available for work, and actively seeking employment.","source":{"name":"Statistics South Africa","shortName":"Stats SA","url":"https://www.statssa.gov.za/?page_id=1854&PPN=P0211","release":"QLFS Q4 2025"},"lastUpdated":"2026-02-18","series":[{"name":"Youth Unemployment (15–34)","unit":"%","data":[{"label":"Q1 2022","value":46.2},{"label":"Q2 2022","value":47.8},{"label":"Q3 2022","value":46.5},{"label":"Q4 2022","value":45.9},{"label":"Q1 2023","value":47.1},{"label":"Q2 2023","value":47.4},{"label":"Q3 2023","value":46.9},{"label":"Q4 2023","value":46.2},{"label":"Q1 2024","value":45.8},{"label":"Q2 2024","value":46.3},{"label":"Q3 2024","value":46.1},{"label":"Q4 2024","value":45.7},{"label":"Q1 2025","value":46.8},{"label":"Q2 2025","value":46.4},{"label":"Q3 2025","value":46.3},{"label":"Q4 2025","value":45.5}]}]},{"id":"youth-unemployment-1524","categoryId":"unemployment","title":"Youth Unemployment Rate (15–24)","value":"61.2%","rawValue":61.2,"unit":"%","change":-0.6,"changeLabel":"from Q3 2025","trend":"down","description":"Unemployment rate among 15–24 year olds — among the highest in the world. This cohort faces structural barriers including lack of experience, skills mismatch, and geographic concentration of youth outside economic centres.","source":{"name":"Statistics South Africa","shortName":"Stats SA","url":"https://www.statssa.gov.za/?page_id=1854&PPN=P0211","release":"QLFS Q4 2025"},"lastUpdated":"2026-02-18","series":[{"name":"Youth Unemployment (15–24)","unit":"%","data":[{"label":"Q1 2022","value":63.9},{"label":"Q2 2022","value":64.8},{"label":"Q3 2022","value":63.2},{"label":"Q4 2022","value":62.7},{"label":"Q1 2023","value":63.5},{"label":"Q2 2023","value":63.9},{"label":"Q3 2023","value":62.8},{"label":"Q4 2023","value":62.1},{"label":"Q1 2024","value":61.8},{"label":"Q2 2024","value":62.4},{"label":"Q3 2024","value":62},{"label":"Q4 2024","value":61.5},{"label":"Q1 2025","value":62.3},{"label":"Q2 2025","value":62},{"label":"Q3 2025","value":61.8},{"label":"Q4 2025","value":61.2}]}]},{"id":"youth-unemployment-expanded","categoryId":"unemployment","title":"Youth Unemployment — Expanded (15–34)","value":"60.8%","rawValue":60.8,"unit":"%","change":-1.1,"changeLabel":"from Q3 2025","trend":"down","description":"The expanded youth unemployment rate includes discouraged work-seekers — those who have given up actively looking for work. This is a more comprehensive measure of labour market distress among youth.","source":{"name":"Statistics South Africa","shortName":"Stats SA","url":"https://www.statssa.gov.za/?page_id=1854&PPN=P0211","release":"QLFS Q4 2025"},"lastUpdated":"2026-02-18","series":[{"name":"Expanded Youth Unemployment (15–34)","unit":"%","data":[{"label":"Q1 2022","value":63.2},{"label":"Q2 2022","value":64.4},{"label":"Q3 2022","value":63.1},{"label":"Q4 2022","value":62.5},{"label":"Q1 2023","value":63},{"label":"Q2 2023","value":63.8},{"label":"Q3 2023","value":62.9},{"label":"Q4 2023","value":62.4},{"label":"Q1 2024","value":62.1},{"label":"Q2 2024","value":62.7},{"label":"Q3 2024","value":62.4},{"label":"Q4 2024","value":61.8},{"label":"Q1 2025","value":62.5},{"label":"Q2 2025","value":62.2},{"label":"Q3 2025","value":61.9},{"label":"Q4 2025","value":60.8}]}]},{"id":"youth-neet-rate","categoryId":"unemployment","title":"NEET Rate (15–24)","value":"37.2%","rawValue":37.2,"unit":"%","change":-0.4,"changeLabel":"from 2024","trend":"down","description":"Percentage of youth aged 15–24 who are Not in Employment, Education, or Training (NEET). This captures both unemployment and disengagement from the education system — a key indicator of social exclusion risk.","source":{"name":"Statistics South Africa","shortName":"Stats SA","url":"https://www.statssa.gov.za/?page_id=1854&PPN=P0211","release":"QLFS Q4 2025"},"lastUpdated":"2026-02-18","series":[{"name":"NEET Rate (15–24)","unit":"%","data":[{"label":"2019","value":34.5},{"label":"2020","value":41.2},{"label":"2021","value":40.1},{"label":"2022","value":39.3},{"label":"2023","value":38.7},{"label":"2024","value":37.6},{"label":"2025","value":37.2}]}]},{"id":"lfpr-overall","categoryId":"unemployment","title":"Labour Force Participation Rate","value":"60.6%","rawValue":60.6,"unit":"%","change":0.4,"changeLabel":"from Q3 2025","trend":"up","description":"The labour force participation rate (LFPR) is the percentage of the working-age population (15–64) that is economically active — either employed or actively looking for work. South Africa's LFPR remains among the lowest of comparable middle-income countries, partly due to high rates of discouragement.","source":{"name":"Statistics South Africa","shortName":"Stats SA","url":"https://www.statssa.gov.za/?page_id=1854&PPN=P0211","release":"QLFS Q4 2025"},"lastUpdated":"2026-02-18","series":[{"name":"Labour Force Participation Rate","unit":"%","data":[{"label":"Q1 2020","value":59.2},{"label":"Q2 2020","value":55.7},{"label":"Q3 2020","value":56.4},{"label":"Q4 2020","value":58.1},{"label":"Q1 2021","value":57.9},{"label":"Q2 2021","value":58.8},{"label":"Q3 2021","value":59.3},{"label":"Q4 2021","value":59.7},{"label":"Q1 2022","value":60.1},{"label":"Q2 2022","value":59.8},{"label":"Q3 2022","value":60.2},{"label":"Q4 2022","value":60.4},{"label":"Q1 2023","value":59.9},{"label":"Q2 2023","value":60.1},{"label":"Q3 2023","value":60.3},{"label":"Q4 2023","value":60.5},{"label":"Q1 2024","value":60.2},{"label